result.execSummary:
The defendant Sheila A. Davis was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Habitual Criminality], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Sheila A. Davis in court with attorney Brent Harold Debord.  Defendant Sheila A. Davis in custody.  Jill Louise Laufenberg appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Court calls 14CM178, 14CM181, 15CM90,15CF78, 16CM60,14CM170 and 16CF51 @ 1:40 p.m. Agreement stated - 14CM170, 14CM178 State moves to dismiss and read in. 14CM181 Def will plead to ct 1, ct 2 dismiss and read in, withheld sentence, probation 3 yrs, court costs, AODA and follow through, counseling as deemed necessary, 8 days credit if revoked. 15CF78 amended information filed, Def will plead to charge, withheld sent, 3 yrs probation with same conditions, 60 days jail commence immediately, 86 days credit if revoked, bond to be applied to costs, with any remainder applied to other cases beginning with oldest. 14CM181 - State will withdraw request to forfeit bond, and apply to costs. 15CM90 - dismissed and read in. 16CM60 - State has compled with VWNR also for 15CF78. 16CM60 Def will plead to ct 1, State would move to dismiss ct 2 and dom ab enhancer on ct 1; 3 yrs probation, same conditions, no jail, 7 days credit if revoked. 16CF51, plead to ct 2, ct 1 dismiss and read in, withheld sent 3 yrs probation, same conditions, no jail, no credit if revoked. Atty Debord agrees. Def understands and agrees. State grants motion to dismiss ct 1 of 16CF51. 15CF78 Court grants motion to amend ct 1. State advises that an additional conditions of probation are no use of alcohol and no presence in taverns. Atty Debord agrees. Plea quest. reviewed. 16CM60 ct 1 - no contest. 14CM181 ct 1 - no contest. 15CF78 ct 1 as amended - no contest. 16CF51 ct 2 - no contest. Court grants motions to dismiss and read in 14CM178, 15CM90, 16CM60 ct 2, 14CM181 ct 2, 14CM170, 15CF78 cts 2 & 3. 16CF51 ct 1 - dismissed out right. Constitutional rights, elements, possible penalties reviewed. Atty Debord satisfied. Court finds Def understands and pleas freely & voluntarily made. Factual basis. Court accepts pleas and finds Def guilty of 16CM60 ct 1 disorderly conduct as repeater (dom ab enhancer is dismissed), 14CM181 ct 1 misd bail jumping, 15CF78 ct 1 as amended - interfere w/child custody as repeater, 16CF51 ct 2 misd bail jumping. Counsel heard on sentencing. Statement by Defendant. Remarks by the Court. 16CM60 ct 1 - sentence withheld, 3 yrs probation, credit for 7 days if revoked, court costs, DNA sample and surcharge, AODA and follow through, counseling as deemed appropriate, no use of alcohol, no presence in taverns. $200 bond applied to costs. 14CM181 ct 1 - sentence withheld, 3 yrs probation, court costs, (no DNA) same conditions, credit for 8 days if revoked. Apply bond. 15CF78 ct 1 - sentence withheld, 3 yrs probation, same conditions as two prior, credit for 86 days if revoked. Additional condition - 60 days jail, commence today, huber as allowed by jail, apply bond  - DNA surcharge on this case. Apply any remaining bond to oldest cases. 16CF51 ct 2 - withheld sentence, 3 yrs probation, same conditions, no credit if revoked, DNA surcharge. Def advised of firearms and voting restrictions.   If probation is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered, without further order of the court, against the defendant in favor of restitution victims and/or governmental entities for the balance due.  All available enforcement actions will be used to collect the debt. Postconviction rights. Any bonds in dismissed cases apply to costs beginning with oldest cases first.
